The algorithm that made youtube is the same one that will kill it. in my experience youtube is still good if you stick exclusively to small channels.
what i do is that every year i delete my yt browsing history, then i change settings so that youtube doesnt use my browsing history to recommend me garbage, then i avoid youtube channels with 100k subs and i dont watch any videos if they have more than 100k views.
every time i see a channel or video like that in my recommendation i click "don't recommend" and if im on mobile i report for "spam or misleading" and then i hit dont recommend.
takes a while but eventually the algorithm starts recommending small channels.
the only downside is that almost all of them have shit audio but i take that over soulless mass produced garbage exclusively designed to get clicks.

I've not got to the main island story section yet, but if I were you, I'd highly recommend just watching the flashbacks section cause I think it really builds the characters well, and is somehow more watchable than the flashbacks in the original show. I think this is cause the flashbacks aren't interrupting crazy island action, and cliffhangers.

I didn't watch Lost when it was airing, so I'm not sure about the history of different fan edits, but "Chronologically LOST" which seems to be the main complete fan edit, is like every scene in the show edited into supposed Chronological order, including all flashbacks and even stuff from "Lost: the missing pieces." It's basically like getting all the flashbacks first, leading up to the crash and then you get the on-island storyline, and the season 6 flash-sideways are the final section.

The only complication is the time travel, which is presented in strict chronological order, so it can be a bit jarring, because it doesn't really make narrative sense. There's also weird things that don't quite fit into chronological order such as Desmond's Flashes Before your Eyes which is a huge part of Desmond's back story but Chronologically Lost decides to present this when we see it in the actual show as a sort of dream sequence. And there's a bunch of other things that are disputed by fans as to whether or not they are correct chronologically.

There's also a new fan edit in the works called "LOST: CIRCLE - A Chronological Fan Edit" which is going to keep the time travel section separate so that it isn't a jumbled mess near the start of it, but will actually be shown in order of when the time travel happens to the characters, like in the original show. And it has a bunch of other improvements upon "Chronologically LOST" to make it more cohesive and cinematic and less like an obvious fan edit, but more like an actual show.

>>179872314
Avatar is so taut and perfectly layered that it makes my head spin. It clearly wasn't trying to please everyone, though, as evidenced by the plebs on here. It has a real vision and real ambitions. If you want a simple narrative and paint-by-numbers film making, go watch your shoot-em-up cop films and "capeshit".
Avatar appeals to the few of us who enjoy challenging complexity. Cameron knows that the public is aware of Dances With Wolves; that's precisely why he references it (and probably 50+ other American films). This is called an homage, and the masters use homage to keep a "conversation with history" going. He includes well-worn tropes and plot points to lure you into a far grander story. The very best artists do this. They leave breadcrumbs in their stories that work as subtext and establishing a film in cinematic history. The fact that you can't see this says a lot about your general lack of expertise in the subject of cinema. There's pretty much unanimous consensus among scholars that Avatar is a western masterpiece... One of the very few that stands shoulder-to-shoulder with Citizen Kane or Lawrence of Arabia.

Don't you see that the "story" is secondary to the "experience". Go watch Nickelodeon for "stories". Avatar is something more than that. It's an entire living, breathing world. And it poetically mirrors the horrors in our world, our Pandora: America.
The film writes the book on centuries of US history. Conquest, technology, expansion, death... It's all there. Cameron's canvas is far too large for small men to behold, I suppose. Go back to redit and have Guardians if the Galaxy spoon-fed to you. The narrative if Avatar is no more or no less than the march of Western Civilization. That's what it chronicles, that's the SUBTEXT, you ape.

The Omaticaya obvs, they're a more simple human self-insert, needed to establish the first go-around to sell it to the audience in the first place, and not as "niche". Also no stupid zoomie haircuts.

>>179873726

I see your scholarly folkloric reading. When Lo'ak removes the dart from Payakan's fin, it is an obvious re-telling of the fable of removing the thorn from the lion's paw. And all of these tropes and ideas are woven together for a new, cohesive whole. My overall favorite thing about the sequel is Lo'ak's alone time, and how it drives the story forward. It helps that Lo'ak is cute. Neteyam is more his mother's son, while Lo'ak is the one who really takes risks, talks shit and takes after dad more. Lo'ak is my favorite. With respect to Saint Kiri (PBUH), she, like Lo'ak, is a middle child and awkward, and she is dealing with a deeper identity crisis than Lo'ak is. Neteyam is self-assured in his identity, and Tuk is too young. This is a film about the awkward middle children finding their way, and that's becoming clearer to me.

While on the subject of folklore itself, the Metkayina leader has a very nice beat of storytelling, conveying the world to those who listen, although he's pretty pissed during the telling.

>>179880998
The French Dispatch felt like someone hired a low brow director to film a knockoff script from the backroom in the style of Wes Anderson. The in your face quirks and shots from his films are distilled and concentrated to such a degree that it resembles parody. There's no balance to it at all. There's no fun quirky Wes shots followed by still stylish but more regular grounded shots for regular progression and depth of style.

While the black and white parts were really nicely shot the small flash to colour really highlights what you're missing out from. In a similar way, the way he's made it an anthology has done it a complete disservice too. Wes' characters have been by far the best with time to grow and develop and nobody is afforded that time here, where he's felt the need to add yet another quirky Wes cast member. The whole thing is so extravagant and indulgent that it feels neutered and impassionate.
